Intro to Tidyquant

Jose Lopez Torres

January 18, 2019

Background

So here we are, fellow reader, at the point where you need to include some financial information in a report, and want to do something more interesting than copying images from Google. Dont want to go through the (very detailed) guide available on CRAN? Alright, read on then.

Tidyquant is a package that integrates information from reputable sources (Bloomberg, Yahoo Finance, etc.), and makes it readily available as tibbles for use in r. If you are an absolute beginner, I suggest that you start by downloading rstudio from this link, where you will be able to run the code that is referenced in this post.

Getting Started

The first step towards using this package is installing it on r. It is as simple as running the following command from your r console:

install.packages('tidyquant')

And presto, were ready to go! Just remember, before using functions from this package, you have to load the library (were adding three at once here, in order to ease our handling of dates and to be more organized with our charts).

library(lubridate)
library(tidyquant)
library(gridExtra)

So, what can we do with it?

Now, were going to focus in some of the functions of Tidyquant. If youd like to know how far this package can take you, run the following instruction:

tq_get_options()
##  [1] "stock.prices"        "stock.prices.google" "stock.prices.japan" 
##  [4] "financials"          "key.ratios"          "dividends"          
##  [7] "splits"              "economic.data"       "exchange.rates"     
## [10] "metal.prices"        "quandl"              "quandl.datatable"   
## [13] "alphavantager"       "rblpapi"

This will display some of the options available as you dive deeper and advance your quest. For the purpose of this tutorial, Ill focus onstock price data. It is enough for you to know that this package supports information retrieval of exchanges (NYSE, NASDAQ), currencies (USD, CAD, EUR, JPY) and even metals.

Alright, so to start Ill pick a stock. Lets go with Tesla.

TSLA <- tq_get("TSLA", get = "stock.prices", from = "2018-08-01", to = "2019-01-18")

glimpse(TSLA)
## Observations: 117
## Variables: 7
## $ date     <date> 2018-08-01, 2018-08-02, 2018-08-03, 2018-08-06, 2018...
## $ open     <dbl> 297.99, 328.44, 347.81, 345.46, 343.84, 369.09, 365.5...
## $ high     <dbl> 303.00, 349.99, 355.00, 354.98, 387.46, 382.64, 367.0...
## $ low      <dbl> 293.00, 323.16, 342.53, 341.82, 339.15, 367.12, 345.7...
## $ close    <dbl> 300.84, 349.54, 348.17, 341.99, 379.57, 370.34, 352.4...
## $ volume   <dbl> 10129400, 23215000, 13656500, 8564300, 30875800, 2457...
## $ adjusted <dbl> 300.84, 349.54, 348.17, 341.99, 379.57, 370.34, 352.4...

In this case, we used the symbol for Tesla (TSLA), to pull information between August 1st, 2018 and January 18th, 2019. You can replace those dates with a timeframe that suits you better, for instance using today() as the end date.

As you can see on the table above, tq_get() finds intra-day information, like opening, closing, high and low prices, as well as transaction volume and adjusted value for the stock (to correct for splits).

Pretty neat, right? So what if you want to plot your own charts? You can use Tidyquant together with ggplot2 in order to create those. To achieve this, simply load library(ggplot2) (assuming you previously installed the package install.packages('ggplot2')), and wield more r power in your hands.

Do you want to see the closing price for Tesla over the period we quoted a few lines ago? Simply run:

library(ggplot2)

tsl <- ggplot(TSLA, aes(date, close)) + geom_line() +
  labs(title = "Tesla closing prices", 
       y = "Closing Price (in U$)",
       x = "Date") + 
  theme_tq()

plot(tsl)

Whoa! The chart is showing the daily closing price for Tesla for the 6-month period starting at the beginning of August.

What else can we do?

So this was a pretty neat plot (maybe not Bloomberg quality yet, but we created it ourselves!), but it most likely wont solve your charting needs for that report youre working on. You might need to add more information, so lets dig in.

You might very likely need to add a trendline to a chart, and the creators of this package really made our lives easier with the tq_mutate() function. The mutate_fun parameter is where the magic happens, as it allows you to choose the calculation that is going to be performed on your data, such as finding a MACD, EMA, volatility or returns. Each option has its own parameters, and you can learn more by punching tq_mutate_fun_options() on the terminal.

For the sake of keeping you interested and keeping this tutorial brief (otherwise youd read one of the longer ones available, right?) Were going to focus on the Moving Average Convergence Divergence (MACD). Were going to follow the standard 12 and 26-period EMAs for the short and long-terms, as well as the 9-period EMA as the signal. This function will only calculate the MACD and signal values, though, so if we need the histogram representing the difference, we need to use the mutate() function, too.

tsl <- TSLA %>%
    filter(date >= as_date("2018-09-15")) %>%
    ggplot(aes(date, close)) + 
    geom_line() +
    labs(title = "TSLA", 
       y = "Closing Price (in U$)",
       x = "Date") + 
    theme_tq() + 
    theme(axis.title.x=element_blank(),
        axis.text.x=element_blank(),
        axis.ticks.x=element_blank())

TSLA_MACD <- TSLA %>%
    tq_mutate(select = close, 
              mutate_fun = MACD, 
              nFast      = 12, 
              nSlow      = 26, 
              nSig       = 9, 
              maType     = EMA) %>%
    mutate(diff = macd - signal) %>%
    filter(date >= as_date("2018-09-15"))

mcd <- TSLA_MACD %>%
    ggplot(aes(x = date)) + 
    geom_line(aes(y = macd)) +
    geom_line(aes(y = signal), color = "blue", linetype = 2) +
    geom_bar(aes(y = diff), 
             stat = "identity",
             color = "black",
             fill = "darkgrey") +
    labs(y = "", x = "Date", color = "") +
    theme_tq()

grid.arrange(tsl, mcd, ncol = 1)

Notice that the first date was modified, since the parameters we used for the MACD indicator generate an offset. Also notice were using a third package: gridExtra. This package allows one chart (price) to be on top of the other (MACD.

One final improvement we can make on this graph is switching the closing price line for a more detailed candlestick chart. This only needs a minor tweak to the chart type, as Tidyquant already downloaded all the necessary information.

tsl <- TSLA %>%
    filter(date >= as_date("2018-09-15")) %>%
    ggplot(aes(date, close)) + 
    geom_candlestick(aes(open = open, 
                         high = high, 
                         low = low, 
                         close = close)) +
    labs(title = "Tesla stock price and MACD indicators", 
       y = "Price (in U$)",
       x = "Date") + 
    theme_tq() + 
    theme(axis.title.x=element_blank(),
        axis.text.x=element_blank(),
        axis.ticks.x=element_blank())

TSLA_MACD <- TSLA %>%
    tq_mutate(select = close, 
              mutate_fun = MACD, 
              nFast      = 12, 
              nSlow      = 26, 
              nSig       = 9, 
              maType     = EMA) %>%
    mutate(diff = macd - signal) %>%
    filter(date >= as_date("2018-09-15"))

mcd <- TSLA_MACD %>%
    ggplot(aes(x = date)) + 
    geom_line(aes(y = macd)) +
    geom_line(aes(y = signal), color = "blue", linetype = 2) +
    geom_bar(aes(y = diff), 
             stat = "identity",
             color = "black",
             fill = "darkgrey") +
    labs(y = "", x = "Date", color = "") +
    theme_tq()

grid.arrange(tsl, mcd, ncol = 1)

It might be more evident now that there is no data for weekends, as the stock wasnt negotiated during these periods.

Is there anything beyond Tesla?

Ok! Lets track more stock using Tidyquant. To start, lets choose different tickers. We like tech, so lets choose something interesting, and create a vector with 6 new codes: AAPL for Apple; AMZN for Amazon; GOOG for Alphabet; NFLX for Netflix; TWTR for Twitter and FB for Facebook.

To look up symbols, try using a search engine.

tickers <- c("AAPL", "AMZN", "GOOG", "NFLX", "TWTR", "FB") %>% 
  tq_get(from = "2018-08-01", to = "2019-01-18")

palette <- c("NFLX" = '#e6194b', 
             "AAPL" = '#e6beff', 
             "AMZN" = '#3cb44b', 
             "FB" = '#4363d8',
             "GOOG" = '#fabebe',
             "TWTR" = '#46f0f0')

For the sake of keeping track of our symbols throughout charts, we set up a color code for each equity.

Now, lets plot the prices. The procedure is very similar to that of plotting Tesla. Needless to say, we must take a step back and drop the candlesticks we added in the final step of the previous excercise, as well as the MACD, for the sake of making a compelling visualization.

superb_plot <- tickers %>% 
  ggplot(aes(date, close, 
             color = fct_reorder(symbol, 
                                 close, 
                                 .fun = last,
                                 .desc = TRUE))) + 
  geom_line() + 
  labs(title = "Now we're tracking more symbols!", 
       x = "Date", 
       y = "Closing price, in U$",
       fill = "Symbol") + 
  scale_colour_manual(values = palette) +
  theme_tq() + 
  theme(legend.position="right", 
        legend.title=element_blank())

plot(superb_plot)

Notice that were not comparing apples to apples here (hehehe), since these equities are priced at different levels. Which of them were really a good investment for the period under study? To answer this question, we should transform the prices under a common denominator. It is possible to set the original stock value at date 1 (August 1st) to 100. From there, itll be easy to understand how each stock behaved, and well see which one outperformed the rest.

superb_plot_scaled <- tickers %>% 
  group_by(symbol) %>% 
  mutate(scaled = 100*close/close[1]) %>% 
  ungroup()

ggplot(superb_plot_scaled, 
       aes(date, scaled, 
           color = fct_reorder(symbol, 
                               scaled, 
                               .fun = last, 
                               .desc = TRUE))) + 
  geom_line() + 
  labs(title = "Now we can compare Apples to [not] Apples", 
       y = "Scaled Price (Based on Aug 1st)", 
       x = "Date") + 
  scale_colour_manual(values = palette) +
  theme_tq() + 
  theme(legend.position="right", 
        legend.title=element_blank())

Great! So Netflix would have been the best bet for the period. If only we could turn back time, we could have made roughly 1 dollar for every 20 invested in that company in under six months.

One final note: if you really need to plot candlestick charts with different stocks, there is a rather simple way. To maximize the visual information carried by these graphs, we can simply add facets for each symbol by tweaking a chart we already used:

superb_plot_faceted <- tickers %>% 
  ggplot(aes(date, close, group = symbol)) + 
  geom_candlestick(aes(open = open, 
                         high = high, 
                         low = low, 
                         close = close)) + 
  facet_wrap(~symbol, ncol = 3, scale = "free_y") +
  labs(title = "Candles for All", 
       x = "Date", 
       y = "Price, in U$",
       fill = "Symbol") + 
  theme_tq()

plot(superb_plot_faceted)

The size of thevisuals will be reduced, making them more difficult to read; however, faceted charts help us understand different behaviours in the information were analyzing. Notice that the Y-axis was freed, so we cant make direct comparisons regarding stock price; however, we can compare trends, just like in our previous chart.
